When `parseQueryString=true`: `parsedUrl.query = {foo: ''}`, `parsedUrl.search = '?foo'`
When `parseQueryString=false`: `parsedUrl.query = 'foo'`, `parsedUrl.search = '?foo'`

In `URL.format`, when `query` is an object, it uses `querystring.stringify(query)`. When `query` is a non-object (string), it falls back to `search`. So with `true`, `?foo` becomes `?foo=` (empty value stringified). With `false`, it stays `?foo`.

But the second parse (which is `true` in both original and mutated) would re-parse the URL. So the final `ret.url` might differ.

